.TH VGP 1 "User Commands"
.SH NAME
vgp \- Parse a Valgrind logfile and present in human readable form
.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBvgp\fR <\fIfilename\fR>
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBvgp\fR parses a log file generated by Valgrind and creates a more human readable version. It will remove
extraneous info like PIDs and adresses. In addition, it will list the source for the offending C/C++ function,
highlighting the line causing the issue. For best results, compile your application with debug information
enabled. Use the \fI-g\fR or \fI-g3\fR options for gcc. It also is suggested that you compile your source
files with the full pathname and run Valgrind with the \fI--fullpath-after=string\fR option. This will enable
\fBvgp\fR to find the source files even if they reside in different directories.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
<\fIfilename\fR>
The path to the input file. This is a required argument.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
\fBvalgrind --leak-check=full --log-file=valgrind-out.txt --fullpath-after=string ./your_program\fR
Run Valgrind and generate a log file with full pathnames enabled.
.TP
\fBvgp valgrind_out.txt\fR
Processes the log file named "valgrind_out.txt" and output the results to stdout.
.TP
\fBvgp valgrind_out.txt > output.txt\fR
Processes the log file named "valgrind_out.txt" and redirect the output to a file named "output.txt".
